{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Sd2LYnGNqZaMyPJpiZA2yW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the current state. The namespace has:\n- Two test pods (curl-test and openssl-toolbox)\n- The elastic-password secret\n- The es-http-tls secret\n- Standard kube-root-ca.crt configmap\n\nI need to deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources. Let me:\n\n1. Create a ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. Create a headless Service for internal pod communication (for cluster formation)\n3. Create the es-http Service for external access\n4. Create a PodDisruptionBudget\n5. Create a StatefulSet with 3 nodes\n\nFor the Elasticsearch configuration, I'll set up cluster discovery using the headless service, enable TLS with the existing secret, and configure authentication with the elastic-password secret. The key settings include the cluster name, discovery seed hosts pointing to the headless service, initial master nodes for all three replicas, and enabling security features for both HTTP and inter-node transport.\n\nFor transport TLS between nodes, I have a few options: reuse the HTTP certificates for simplicity in development, disable it (less secure), or generate separate transport certificates. I'll go with using the same certificate from the es-http-tls secret for both HTTP and transport communication to keep the setup straightforward.\n\nNow I'm creating the Kubernetes manifests. I need a headless service for cluster discovery on port 9300, a regular HTTP service on port 9200 for client access, and a ConfigMap to define the Elasticsearch configuration.\n\nWriting config file...\n\nI need to figure out how Elasticsearch 8.x handles the initial password setup—specifically whether setting the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable will automatically configure the built-in elastic user when the cluster first starts.\n\nFor the StatefulSet itself, I'm thinking through the resource allocation for a 3-node development cluster—probably around 512Mi to 1Gi of memory per node with 0.5 to 1 core of CPU. The key thing is that with a StatefulSet and headless service, the pods get predictable DNS names like `es-0.es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, which I can use for the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` configuration since Elasticsearch uses the hostname as the node identifier.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the transport SSL setup. The HTTP service certificate might have SANs configured for the HTTP endpoint, not for inter-node transport communication. I could either disable transport SSL entirely for this dev setup and just rely on HTTPS for the HTTP port, or figure out a separate certificate strategy for transport.\n\nBut wait—in Elasticsearch 8.x, when security is enabled, transport SSL becomes mandatory by default, so I need to configure it properly. I'm thinking about using the same certificate for both HTTP and transport with a verification mode that checks certificate validity without strict hostname matching, which should work if they share the same CA.\n\nFor the Kubernetes setup, I need to set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable to initialize the built-in elastic user, and since there's no NetworkPolicy constraint mentioned, the default allow-all networking should be sufficient. Let me start writing out the manifests now. Writing Kubernetes manifests... Writing Kubernetes config... Configuring resource requests and limits for the container, then setting up the persistent volume claim template for data storage. I'm also considering whether to include a privileged init container to set the vm.max_map_count kernel parameter that Elasticsearch needs, though this depends on the security policies of the Kubernetes cluster. Adding readiness probe configuration... Adding probe configuration...\n\nI need to think through the initialization details for the Elasticsearch cluster. With the node names derived from the pod names via the downward API, the initial master nodes should be `es-0`, `es-1`, and `es-2`. The discovery mechanism also needs to properly reference the headless service for inter-node communication. Right, so with a headless service, Kubernetes DNS will return all the individual pod IPs when ES queries `es-nodes`, which means discovery should work seamlessly. Now I'm putting together the complete manifest file and thinking through the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` handling—setting it from the secret ensures all nodes use the same password, though I need to be careful since it only takes effect on first initialization before the cluster is fully set up.\n\nFor the 3-node cluster, I should add a PodDisruptionBudget with `minAvailable: 2` to maintain quorum during disruptions. I'm also considering the security constraints—the init container might need adjustments depending on the cluster's security policies, and I need to decide between using PersistentVolumeClaims or emptyDir for storage, keeping in mind that kind clusters typically have a default storage class available.\n\nWriting the complete manifest... I'm getting confused about how Elasticsearch handles environment variables for configuration. Let me clarify: Elasticsearch supports variable substitution in the config file using `${VAR_NAME}` syntax, so I can set `node.name: ${NODE_NAME}` in elasticsearch.yml and pass the NODE_NAME env var to the pod.\n\nWriting the StatefulSet config... Writing the ConfigMap manifest... I need to verify the secret key names match what's mounted—`tls.crt`, `tls.key`, and `ca.crt` at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs`. Now I'm thinking through whether to use a privileged init container for the sysctl settings or explore alternatives, since some environments restrict privileged containers. Since I don't have the namespace security configuration, I'll make the manifest flexible by including a privileged init container with a fallback that won't break if it fails. For a kind cluster, the host usually has the right vm.max_map_count setting already, but including the init container as best practice is safer. Now I need to think through the readiness and liveness probe configuration.\n\nI'm setting up a readiness probe that checks the Elasticsearch cluster health endpoint with proper authentication, using the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable to verify the container is actually ready to serve requests before marking it as ready.\n\nLet me write out the complete manifest now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":789,"cache_read_input_tokens":28252,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":789},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"279f27af-7143-4116-9f52-e911a9a445e0","uuid":"05a52b9f-ef17-4772-bda0-ecb9df3ef39a","request_id":"req_011Cc6jgRWM9YxrW4PDLD8Gx"}
